{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/hypertension-not-diabetic/background-information/risk-factors/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"3e698434-11c9-553c-96a6-a249bf121cbb","slug":"risk-factors","fullItemName":"Risk factors","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 140f3ca3-f554-4ba8-a57a-a7690106b506 --><h2>What are the risk factors?</h2><!-- end field 140f3ca3-f554-4ba8-a57a-a7690106b506 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 9b91be57-500b-4303-9452-a7690106b045 --><!-- begin field c533528b-cee5-4986-ab98-a7690106b506 --><ul><li><strong>Risk factors for hypertension include:</strong><ul><li>Age — blood pressure tends to rise with advancing age.</li><li>Sex — Up to about 65 years, women tend to have a lower blood pressure than men. Between 65 to 74 years of age, women tend to have a higher blood pressure.</li><li>Ethnicity — people of Black African and Black Caribbean origin are more likely to be diagnosed with hypertension.</li><li>Genetic factors — research on twins suggest that up to 40% of variability in blood pressure may be explained by genetic factors.</li><li>Social deprivation — people from the most deprived areas in England are 30% more likely to have hypertension than those from the least deprived.</li><li>Lifestyle — smoking, excessive alcohol consumption, excess dietary salt, obesity, and lack of physical activity are associated with hypertension.</li><li>Anxiety and emotional stress — can raise blood pressure due to increased adrenaline and cortisol levels. </li></ul></li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hypertension-not-diabetic/references/\">PHE, 2017</a>]</p><!-- end field c533528b-cee5-4986-ab98-a7690106b506 --><!-- end item 9b91be57-500b-4303-9452-a7690106b045 -->","topic":{"id":"c1c1e500-a3f1-5baa-8d5f-890b15f767cc","topicId":"8de59d12-a526-4ab9-8496-1fcb59d838ff","topicName":"Hypertension - not diabetic","slug":